03909nam a2200577Ia 9780791477182DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97807914771827 a10.1515/97807914771822doi  a(DE-B1597)683359  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD804.348b.B477 2009eb 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a940.53/182221 aBernard-Donals, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForgetful Memory :bRepresentation and Remembrance in the Wake of the Holocaust /cMichael Bernard-Donals. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (212 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tMemory and Forgetting -- tOn the Verge of History and Memory -- tEthics, the Immemorial, and Writing -- tWriting and the Disaster -- t“If I forget thee, O Jerusalem” -- tMemory and the Image in Visual Representations of the Holocaust -- t“Thou Shalt Not Bear False Witness” -- tMemory and the Event -- tDenials of Memory -- tConflations of Memory; or, What They Saw at the Holocaust Museum after 9/11 -- t“Difficult Freedom” -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMuch of the discussion surrounding the Holocaust and how it can be depicted sixty years later has focused on memory. In Forgetful Memory, Michael Bernard-Donals focuses on the relation between memory and forgetfulness, arguing that memory and forgetfulness cannot be separated but must be examined as they complicate our understanding of the Shoah. Drawing on the work of Josef Yerushalmi, Maurice Blanchot, David Roskies, and especially Emmanuel Levinas, Bernard-Donals explores contemporary representations of the Holocaust in memoirs, novels, and poetry; films and photographs; in museums; and in our contemporary political discourse concerning the Middle East. Ultimately, Forgetful Memory makes the case that we should give up on the idea of memory as a kind of representation, and that we should see it instead as an intersection of remembrance and oblivion, as a kind of writing, where what remains at its margins—what is left unwritten—is at least as important as what is given voice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xHistoriography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xMoral and ethical aspects. 0aMemoryxSocial aspects. 4aHistory : Historiography. 4aHistory : History. 4aHistory : Holocaust Studies. 4aHistory : World War II. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147718240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791477182423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791477182/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles